    link: 'https://demo.worona.org/small-and-picturesque-french-villages/',
    title: { rendered: 'Picturesque French Villages' },
    content: {
      rendered:
        '<p>With 83 million foreign tourists in 2012, France is ranked as the first tourist destination in the world, ahead of the US (67 million) and China (58 million). <!--more-->This 83 million figure excludes people staying less than 24 hours, such as North Europeans crossing France on their way to Spain or Italy. It is third in income from tourism due to shorter duration of visits. France has 37 sites inscribed in <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_World_Heritage_Sites_in_France" target="_blank">UNESCO&#8217;s World Heritage List</a> and features cities of high cultural interest, beaches and seaside resorts, ski resorts, and rural regions that many enjoy for their beauty and tranquillity (green tourism).</p>\n<h3>Les Plus Beaux Villages</h3>\n<p><img class="alignnone wp-image-88 size-large" src="https://demo.worona.org/wp-content/uploads/2016/11/france-village-1024x658.jpg" alt="french village" width="840" height="540" srcset="https://demo.worona.org/wp-content/uploads/2016/11/france-village-1024x658.jpg 1024w, https://demo.worona.org/wp-content/uploads/2016/11/france-village-300x193.jpg 300w, https://demo.worona.org/wp-content/uploads/2016/11/france-village-768x493.jpg 768w, https://demo.worona.org/wp-content/uploads/2016/11/france-village-1200x771.jpg 1200w" sizes="(max-width: 709px) 85vw, (max-width: 909px) 67vw, (max-width: 1362px) 62vw, 840px" /></p>\n<p>Small and picturesque French villages are promoted through the association Les Plus Beaux Villages de France (litt. &#8220;The Most Beautiful Villages of France&#8221;). The &#8220;Remarkable Gardens&#8221; label is a list of the over 200 gardens classified by the French Ministry of Culture. This label is intended to protect and promote remarkable gardens and parks. France attracts many religious pilgrims on their way to St. James, or to Lourdes, a town in the Hautes-Pyr\u00e9n\u00e9es that hosts several million visitors a year.</p>\n<h3>The French Riviera</h3>\n<p>With more than 10 millions tourists a year, the French Riviera (or C\u00f4te d&#8217;Azur), in south-east France, is the second leading tourist destination in the country, after the Paris region. It benefits from 300 days of sunshine per year, 115 kilometres of coastline and beaches, 18 golf courses, 14 ski resorts and 3,000 restaurants. Each year the C\u00f4te d&#8217;Azur hosts 50% of the world&#8217;s superyacht fleet.</p>\n<p>Source: <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/France#Tourism">France</a>.</p>\n',
      protected: false,
    },
